WEBVTT

00:00:00.719 --> 00:00:06.080
Okay, so let's continue our discussion

00:00:03.919 --> 00:00:09.679
on using transformers

00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:14.160
in large data sets to obtain pre-trained

00:00:09.679 --> 00:00:17.279
models. And here we want to switch from

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:20.400
the vision transformers to language

00:00:17.279 --> 00:00:22.800
models. So the vision transformer idea

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:25.840
actually came after what we are going to

00:00:22.800 --> 00:00:29.359
talk about today. Transformers were

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:31.599
initially developed to handle text data

00:00:29.359 --> 00:00:35.760
initially in machine translation which

00:00:31.599 --> 00:00:39.840
had an encoder and a decoder part to

00:00:35.760 --> 00:00:42.399
take in a sequence and output

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:44.879
another sequence. But then later

00:00:42.399 --> 00:00:49.280
different parts of the transformer prove

00:00:44.879 --> 00:00:53.120
to be useful. And uh Bert here is a way

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:56.559
of encoding text just what just like

00:00:53.120 --> 00:01:00.320
what we did for vision transformers

00:00:56.559 --> 00:01:04.239
to classify that text. But we first saw

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:06.960
that idea in image classification and

00:01:04.239 --> 00:01:10.159
the main reason was we are very familiar

00:01:06.960 --> 00:01:13.920
with that since we developed the CNN's

00:01:10.159 --> 00:01:16.880
there and we already saw this potential

00:01:13.920 --> 00:01:20.320
for learning representations across

00:01:16.880 --> 00:01:23.040
images and text. So that basically help

00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:25.520
us to double down on this idea of

00:01:23.040 --> 00:01:27.840
transfer learning learning a pre-trained

00:01:25.520 --> 00:01:31.439
model and then use it for specific

00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:34.400
tasks. We want to try that idea in text

00:01:31.439 --> 00:01:36.000
and we look at three different

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:38.400
architectures

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:40.640
all transformerbased.

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:43.600
BERT which is the encoder part of the

00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:47.040
trans transformer. GPT is only the

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:48.560
decoder part and T5 is the entire

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:52.479
architecture.

00:01:48.560 --> 00:01:54.960
So these names Bert, GPG and T5 are like

00:01:52.479 --> 00:01:57.200
the most famous person in this family

00:01:54.960 --> 00:01:59.840
basically that becomes like a last name

00:01:57.200 --> 00:02:02.960
really. But for example in the decoder

00:01:59.840 --> 00:02:05.920
part we have llama models that is still

00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:08.239
an auto reggressive type of model. Okay.

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:12.239
So we discuss how to train these models

00:02:08.239 --> 00:02:15.599
and later we want to fine-tune them

00:02:12.239 --> 00:02:18.400
right and we discuss the the way that we

00:02:15.599 --> 00:02:21.120
are training them that we call self-s

00:02:18.400 --> 00:02:23.520
supervision that is somehow different

00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:27.280
than what we did for vision. So, back to

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:30.720
computer vision. Let's say we want to

00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:34.080
classify flower types and we have let's

00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:38.000
say 5,000 label flower images and we

00:02:34.080 --> 00:02:41.840
want to train a CNN with 50 million par

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:44.640
with 50 million parameters and we need a

00:02:41.840 --> 00:02:47.120
GPU and maybe a few days of compute or

00:02:44.640 --> 00:02:49.840
less depending on the resources that we

00:02:47.120 --> 00:02:52.879
have. The question is should we train

00:02:49.840 --> 00:02:55.120
from scratch? The answer

00:02:52.879 --> 00:02:59.040
back in 2012

00:02:55.120 --> 00:03:01.440
was no because we were going to be

00:02:59.040 --> 00:03:03.680
overfeit badly with this number of

00:03:01.440 --> 00:03:07.840
parameters with and this number of

00:03:03.680 --> 00:03:12.239
images we cannot get a good model. But

00:03:07.840 --> 00:03:14.640
now that we have a trained CNN possibly

00:03:12.239 --> 00:03:18.879
on a very large data set for example

00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:21.440
imageet we can use it and fine-tune for

00:03:18.879 --> 00:03:23.920
our specific problem. We have done this

00:03:21.440 --> 00:03:25.920
before and the idea is there are some

00:03:23.920 --> 00:03:29.040
universal features that the pre-trained

00:03:25.920 --> 00:03:30.879
model and the large data set learn and

00:03:29.040 --> 00:03:33.680
we don't need to learn that anymore and

00:03:30.879 --> 00:03:36.959
we can transfer them to the new task.

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:40.640
Hence we can copy the pre-train CNN and

00:03:36.959 --> 00:03:43.680
freeze most of the layers and only train

00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:46.480
a few layers that corresponds mostly

00:03:43.680 --> 00:03:49.360
with the new head that is using the same

00:03:46.480 --> 00:03:53.599
features and predict uh different

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:56.400
classes. So after 2012 once we had these

00:03:53.599 --> 00:04:00.879
pre-trained models we can fine-tune them

00:03:56.400 --> 00:04:04.000
on smaller task specific data sets data

00:04:00.879 --> 00:04:06.400
sets that sometimes is very difficult to

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.959
collect for example medical imaging due

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:12.959
to many reasons for example privacy

00:04:08.959 --> 00:04:15.920
related standards and compliances or

00:04:12.959 --> 00:04:19.519
getting good label data. But now that we

00:04:15.920 --> 00:04:22.079
have this set up, we can fine-tune our

00:04:19.519 --> 00:04:26.639
neural network for this finite data

00:04:22.079 --> 00:04:29.520
sets. Hence, this allows us to have

00:04:26.639 --> 00:04:33.360
specialized networks on different

00:04:29.520 --> 00:04:35.520
specialized domains. So by 2015,

00:04:33.360 --> 00:04:37.840
basically this idea was a standard

00:04:35.520 --> 00:04:41.680
practice in computer vision. Now the

00:04:37.840 --> 00:04:44.560
question is can we do the same for text?

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:47.759
If images have edges, textures and

00:04:44.560 --> 00:04:49.919
shapes, well, text has grammar, syntax,

00:04:47.759 --> 00:04:53.919
and semantics too that are general

00:04:49.919 --> 00:04:57.280
features and we can learn. Well, to

00:04:53.919 --> 00:04:59.280
answer that, first we have to say, well,

00:04:57.280 --> 00:05:03.360
for the computer vision, we had this

00:04:59.280 --> 00:05:07.680
very nice data sets that are labeled and

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:10.560
have this clear task for classification.

00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:15.199
Do we have the same for text?

00:05:10.560 --> 00:05:18.639
Well, not really because u comparable

00:05:15.199 --> 00:05:20.240
label data set for text is either

00:05:18.639 --> 00:05:24.320
non-existing

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:27.280
due to the humongous effort that is

00:05:24.320 --> 00:05:31.280
required for labeling them or sometimes

00:05:27.280 --> 00:05:35.440
really the task is not set in stone and

00:05:31.280 --> 00:05:37.759
the task is often time fluid in text. So

00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:40.639
that's a problem and how can we solve

00:05:37.759 --> 00:05:44.400
that? Well, the answer is maybe we don't

00:05:40.639 --> 00:05:46.560
need that and that's how we get to

00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:49.759
self-supervised learning. So the idea is

00:05:46.560 --> 00:05:52.320
well text contains its own supervision.

00:05:49.759 --> 00:05:55.600
Yes, we may not have like cleanly

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:58.320
labeled sentences but we have unlimited

00:05:55.600 --> 00:06:00.800
unlabeled text. For example, we have

00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:04.319
Wikipedia data set with billions of

00:06:00.800 --> 00:06:06.479
tokens, different book data sets again

00:06:04.319 --> 00:06:09.440
with billions of tokens. We have web

00:06:06.479 --> 00:06:12.160
pages that we can design crawlers and

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:14.880
scrapers to collect data from. And

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:17.280
within text, we have an inherent

00:06:14.880 --> 00:06:19.680
structure. For example, we can hide a

00:06:17.280 --> 00:06:23.520
word and the model can predict that. We

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:25.600
can basically hide half of the sentence

00:06:23.520 --> 00:06:27.520
and the model can generate the other

00:06:25.600 --> 00:06:31.360
half. Basically, what I'm trying to say

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:34.240
is text itself provides labels

00:06:31.360 --> 00:06:37.600
if we look differently. This is known as

00:06:34.240 --> 00:06:40.160
self-supervised learning which the model

00:06:37.600 --> 00:06:42.720
creates supervised task for itself from

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:46.400
this unlabeled data. So some other

00:06:42.720 --> 00:06:49.360
question for example let's say we have a

00:06:46.400 --> 00:06:52.560
sentence like I love this red car and

00:06:49.360 --> 00:06:55.840
then we can mask a word here red for

00:06:52.560 --> 00:06:58.800
example and make up a task to predict

00:06:55.840 --> 00:07:02.319
that token so the model can do the

00:06:58.800 --> 00:07:05.919
entire steps no human label is needed.

00:07:02.319 --> 00:07:08.479
Another way of making up labels is to do

00:07:05.919 --> 00:07:10.720
next token prediction. So we have this

00:07:08.479 --> 00:07:15.039
sentence and then we hide the last word

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:18.800
or last token and we ask to predict that

00:07:15.039 --> 00:07:21.440
this is known an auto reggressive task.

00:07:18.800 --> 00:07:24.639
You can think of other madeup super

00:07:21.440 --> 00:07:27.360
signal for shuffling sentences and uh

00:07:24.639 --> 00:07:29.039
asking to restore them where again we

00:07:27.360 --> 00:07:32.639
have the original document that tells us

00:07:29.039 --> 00:07:36.319
the the order. So great can do this for

00:07:32.639 --> 00:07:38.479
text but why we didn't do it for images

00:07:36.319 --> 00:07:41.039
at the first place. Well, the main

00:07:38.479 --> 00:07:43.680
reason was um for text we have a finite

00:07:41.039 --> 00:07:46.880
vocabulary and it's easy to design this

00:07:43.680 --> 00:07:49.440
self-supervised tasks and often it even

00:07:46.880 --> 00:07:51.759
seems natural to do it. For example,

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:54.960
predict this war. I mean we do games

00:07:51.759 --> 00:07:57.360
like that given some context or answers

00:07:54.960 --> 00:07:59.520
for some question we ask the other

00:07:57.360 --> 00:08:02.479
player to predict the war and then we

00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:04.800
can use this very efficient crescent for

00:08:02.479 --> 00:08:06.800
example here.

00:08:04.800 --> 00:08:09.199
That's not the case for images and the

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:11.280
main reason is there we're dealing with

00:08:09.199 --> 00:08:13.280
continuous data and there's not really a

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:15.759
finite vocabulary. We're talking about

00:08:13.280 --> 00:08:19.360
pixel values and it's very hard because

00:08:15.759 --> 00:08:22.639
of that much larger degree of freedom to

00:08:19.360 --> 00:08:25.280
do the training. There are some modern

00:08:22.639 --> 00:08:27.759
way of uh doing self-supervised learning

00:08:25.280 --> 00:08:31.199
for vision now that I'm going to skip

00:08:27.759 --> 00:08:33.760
but back then that was not uh the main

00:08:31.199 --> 00:08:37.519
way of training computer vision models.

00:08:33.760 --> 00:08:41.120
Again, this new updates are available

00:08:37.519 --> 00:08:44.159
now because of the advances in the NLP

00:08:41.120 --> 00:08:47.279
field that trickled down to computer

00:08:44.159 --> 00:08:50.160
vision. Okay, so the transfer learning

00:08:47.279 --> 00:08:52.399
will look different now. And here we

00:08:50.160 --> 00:08:55.279
have this pre-training stage for text

00:08:52.399 --> 00:08:57.760
that is trained on this massive

00:08:55.279 --> 00:09:00.959
unlabeled corpus of text. We're talking

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:03.519
about billions of tokens. And this is

00:09:00.959 --> 00:09:06.560
done in [snorts] a self-supervised

00:09:03.519 --> 00:09:09.360
manner. And this way the model learns

00:09:06.560 --> 00:09:12.880
the general features of the language.

00:09:09.360 --> 00:09:16.240
And then we can transfer that to more

00:09:12.880 --> 00:09:19.279
specialized tasks. For example,

00:09:16.240 --> 00:09:22.080
um with top with thousands of examples

00:09:19.279 --> 00:09:24.959
that has a specific task that we care

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:27.760
about. Later we will see that even given

00:09:24.959 --> 00:09:30.959
if we have a bridge pre-training without

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:34.399
any further training and just by giving

00:09:30.959 --> 00:09:36.399
some context within a prompt we get we

00:09:34.399 --> 00:09:39.040
can get the answers for our question and

00:09:36.399 --> 00:09:41.040
that's where things become very

00:09:39.040 --> 00:09:44.880
interesting. Okay. So let's not jump

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:46.399
ahead and continue from the bird family

00:09:44.880 --> 00:09:49.519
that started this paradigm of

00:09:46.399 --> 00:09:51.279
self-supervised learning. So here we

00:09:49.519 --> 00:09:54.160
focus on bird which is the

00:09:51.279 --> 00:09:56.880
transformerbased version of them which

00:09:54.160 --> 00:09:59.680
is basically an encoder transformer

00:09:56.880 --> 00:10:02.880
trained in a self-supervised manner and

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:06.000
language models and then fine-tune

00:10:02.880 --> 00:10:08.800
on different tasks. The original paper

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:12.000
for bird showed that for all of these

00:10:08.800 --> 00:10:14.320
different NLP tasks achieved

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:17.360
state-of-the-art performance. This

00:10:14.320 --> 00:10:21.279
fine-tuning on these tasks often needed

00:10:17.360 --> 00:10:24.880
only a few thousands of example. So this

00:10:21.279 --> 00:10:27.279
really changed the landscape of NLP

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:30.480
because before bird if we wanted to

00:10:27.279 --> 00:10:33.120
train a model for a specific task we

00:10:30.480 --> 00:10:36.320
needed to design its own architecture

00:10:33.120 --> 00:10:38.720
and its own large label data set and

00:10:36.320 --> 00:10:41.360
eventually achieve a model that only

00:10:38.720 --> 00:10:44.320
does a specific task. But after this

00:10:41.360 --> 00:10:46.880
paradigm shift, one pre-trained model

00:10:44.320 --> 00:10:50.000
can be fine-tuned for different tasks

00:10:46.880 --> 00:10:52.320
often with small data sets and achieve

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:56.640
strong performance. And that's how

00:10:52.320 --> 00:10:58.880
transfer learning became default in NLP.

00:10:56.640 --> 00:11:01.920
So we discussed transform transformer

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:05.200
architecture and we said it's modular.

00:11:01.920 --> 00:11:08.000
It has this encoder decoder modules and

00:11:05.200 --> 00:11:11.680
for these three different families for

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:13.440
example B only uses the encoder GPT only

00:11:11.680 --> 00:11:16.640
uses the decoder and this

00:11:13.440 --> 00:11:18.720
sequencetosequence models uh with this

00:11:16.640 --> 00:11:22.160
flagship T5

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:24.959
model uses both. So if we want to use

00:11:22.160 --> 00:11:26.640
both we need a cross attention right

00:11:24.959 --> 00:11:29.040
otherwise self attention within the

00:11:26.640 --> 00:11:33.120
encoder or decoder is enough. So

00:11:29.040 --> 00:11:36.079
whenever we have only the encoder, we

00:11:33.120 --> 00:11:39.360
don't really need the causal masking. So

00:11:36.079 --> 00:11:42.240
we can look both ways and that's how the

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:44.880
birectional way of training can be

00:11:42.240 --> 00:11:47.600
included in bird for example. And for

00:11:44.880 --> 00:11:50.880
some T5 or sequence to sequence models

00:11:47.600 --> 00:11:53.200
also as long as we're not decoding one

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:56.160
token at a time, we can also train them

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:59.120
in a birectional ways. Okay, so let's

00:11:56.160 --> 00:12:02.320
zoom in into Bert, which only uses the

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:04.480
encoder transformer. Like I said, it's a

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:06.639
birectional self attention, meaning that

00:12:04.480 --> 00:12:09.360
every token can attend to all other

00:12:06.639 --> 00:12:11.760
tokens, and there's no causal mask. We

00:12:09.360 --> 00:12:14.160
really don't need that. And the output

00:12:11.760 --> 00:12:16.639
can be a contextual representation,

00:12:14.160 --> 00:12:19.120
something like the CLS token that we

00:12:16.639 --> 00:12:21.279
discuss in vision transformer. Just like

00:12:19.120 --> 00:12:23.279
vision transformer, they can be great

00:12:21.279 --> 00:12:26.160
for classification, for example,

00:12:23.279 --> 00:12:29.279
sentiment analysis. They can feel or

00:12:26.160 --> 00:12:32.079
replace tokens and they can also

00:12:29.279 --> 00:12:34.480
understand tasks in case we want to use

00:12:32.079 --> 00:12:36.480
that for another reason than

00:12:34.480 --> 00:12:38.720
classification.

00:12:36.480 --> 00:12:41.200
Okay. So let's look at how we are doing

00:12:38.720 --> 00:12:43.920
this uh self-supervised learning in

00:12:41.200 --> 00:12:47.279
bird. So the procedure for that was to

00:12:43.920 --> 00:12:51.760
select 15% of token randomly

00:12:47.279 --> 00:12:56.000
and replace 80% of that 50 15% with mask

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:58.720
tokens. 10% of that 15% with random

00:12:56.000 --> 00:13:00.480
token. Basically, we replace them with

00:12:58.720 --> 00:13:03.519
randomly chosen token from the

00:13:00.480 --> 00:13:06.399
vocabulary and then choose another 10%

00:13:03.519 --> 00:13:11.519
and keep it on change. So, let's zoom

00:13:06.399 --> 00:13:14.959
into uh why this uh 15% is spent like

00:13:11.519 --> 00:13:17.040
this. Note that we choose this tokens

00:13:14.959 --> 00:13:18.800
and we ask the model to predict them.

00:13:17.040 --> 00:13:21.519
When we replace the token with mask

00:13:18.800 --> 00:13:23.519
token, basically the mask token is not

00:13:21.519 --> 00:13:26.160
providing any information about the

00:13:23.519 --> 00:13:29.519
original token. So the model has to look

00:13:26.160 --> 00:13:33.440
around and seek context for that. The

00:13:29.519 --> 00:13:36.399
10% uh of tokens that are replaced with

00:13:33.440 --> 00:13:39.360
a random token is a way to reduce a

00:13:36.399 --> 00:13:42.079
train test mismatch. What I mean is

00:13:39.360 --> 00:13:45.279
basically during the pre-training if the

00:13:42.079 --> 00:13:47.839
model only sees the mask token, it may

00:13:45.279 --> 00:13:49.600
only worry about the tokens

00:13:47.839 --> 00:13:53.200
representation

00:13:49.600 --> 00:13:55.360
uh when it's a mask. So it gets lazy

00:13:53.200 --> 00:13:59.120
with the representation of the non-mask

00:13:55.360 --> 00:14:01.680
tokens. But by swapping in a random word

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:05.440
chosen from the vocabulary, we force the

00:14:01.680 --> 00:14:08.079
model to learn that any word can be

00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:12.000
potentially wrong. So it has to rely on

00:14:08.079 --> 00:14:14.240
the rely on the context to verify or

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:17.440
correct the token that he's looking at.

00:14:14.240 --> 00:14:20.639
So now the question is why we keep 10%

00:14:17.440 --> 00:14:25.279
unchange. The reason is this is a way of

00:14:20.639 --> 00:14:27.920
balancing out this 10% wrong tokens

00:14:25.279 --> 00:14:31.040
because otherwise if we don't have this

00:14:27.920 --> 00:14:35.120
and we have only this basically the

00:14:31.040 --> 00:14:37.839
model learns this bias that any non-mask

00:14:35.120 --> 00:14:41.360
token that I'm asked to predict is

00:14:37.839 --> 00:14:44.160
probably wrong but with keeping this

00:14:41.360 --> 00:14:47.040
unchanged tokens we force the model to

00:14:44.160 --> 00:14:48.639
use the context to confirm if the word

00:14:47.040 --> 00:14:52.639
is correct.

00:14:48.639 --> 00:14:55.440
So in summary, the mask tokens forces

00:14:52.639 --> 00:14:59.839
the model to use the context. The random

00:14:55.440 --> 00:15:02.560
tokens reduces this train test mismatch.

00:14:59.839 --> 00:15:06.399
And in conjunction with this unchanged

00:15:02.560 --> 00:15:09.839
tokens, the model is not sure if a token

00:15:06.399 --> 00:15:11.839
is correct or random. So it must always

00:15:09.839 --> 00:15:15.519
be cross-checking

00:15:11.839 --> 00:15:18.320
uh it against the context. So that's how

00:15:15.519 --> 00:15:22.639
we train the birth model. Note that this

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:25.600
is an encoder model which means that we

00:15:22.639 --> 00:15:28.800
don't need to have a causal mask. So we

00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:32.240
can look from both direction

00:15:28.800 --> 00:15:34.079
which makes the the model uh more sample

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:37.199
efficient compared to those that

00:15:34.079 --> 00:15:40.079
enforces the the causal masking like the

00:15:37.199 --> 00:15:42.880
auto reggressive models like GPT. Okay.

00:15:40.079 --> 00:15:44.959
So how to do fine-tuning? Well, if we

00:15:42.880 --> 00:15:47.519
have a classification task just like

00:15:44.959 --> 00:15:50.560
what we did for vision transformer, we

00:15:47.519 --> 00:15:53.680
use the CLS token um and send it to a

00:15:50.560 --> 00:15:57.839
softmax to get the logits and send it to

00:15:53.680 --> 00:16:01.440
a softmax to get the probabilities.

00:15:57.839 --> 00:16:05.759
So the token classification task is also

00:16:01.440 --> 00:16:08.720
called named entity recognition or ne.

00:16:05.759 --> 00:16:10.880
So the next uh task is really sentence

00:16:08.720 --> 00:16:14.720
pairing. So note uh there is a

00:16:10.880 --> 00:16:17.120
additional token here that basically

00:16:14.720 --> 00:16:19.680
separate the sentences and it's like a

00:16:17.120 --> 00:16:23.120
boundary for each sentence and you

00:16:19.680 --> 00:16:28.560
already know cls token. So this help us

00:16:23.120 --> 00:16:32.000
to now define uh tasks on the sentences

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:34.880
and somehow do natural language

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:39.040
inference which is basically a way of

00:16:34.880 --> 00:16:42.240
recognizing this textual entailment that

00:16:39.040 --> 00:16:45.759
involves logical relationship between uh

00:16:42.240 --> 00:16:47.360
pairs of sentences for example

00:16:45.759 --> 00:16:51.839
contradiction

00:16:47.360 --> 00:16:55.360
u and entailment. So the other family is

00:16:51.839 --> 00:16:57.279
T5. So T5 architectures are using both

00:16:55.360 --> 00:17:00.720
encoder and decoder very similar to

00:16:57.279 --> 00:17:05.199
sequence tosequence models. But here T5

00:17:00.720 --> 00:17:09.520
frames every NLP task as a texttoext

00:17:05.199 --> 00:17:11.760
problem. So the original um transformer

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:15.120
uh from the paper attention is all you

00:17:11.760 --> 00:17:17.760
need. It introduced an architecture. It

00:17:15.120 --> 00:17:21.439
didn't really specify any pre-training

00:17:17.760 --> 00:17:23.760
task just like bird for example and it

00:17:21.439 --> 00:17:26.720
was designed for a single purpose a

00:17:23.760 --> 00:17:29.120
sequencetose sequence task and primarily

00:17:26.720 --> 00:17:32.000
for machine translation.

00:17:29.120 --> 00:17:33.520
T5 uses the same encoder decoder

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:36.320
architecture

00:17:33.520 --> 00:17:39.200
so no modification in the architecture

00:17:36.320 --> 00:17:41.520
but reframes the input and output and

00:17:39.200 --> 00:17:44.960
it's trained differently from the

00:17:41.520 --> 00:17:47.760
transformer. So for example transformer

00:17:44.960 --> 00:17:49.840
really they didn't have a pre-training

00:17:47.760 --> 00:17:52.640
objective they were trained in a

00:17:49.840 --> 00:17:55.280
supervised manner for example

00:17:52.640 --> 00:17:58.720
the machine translation where we had

00:17:55.280 --> 00:18:02.480
pairs of uh sentences uh for example

00:17:58.720 --> 00:18:05.919
from English to German here in T5 we act

00:18:02.480 --> 00:18:08.400
we we have pre-training and the

00:18:05.919 --> 00:18:11.840
different here with uh for example bird

00:18:08.400 --> 00:18:16.240
is here we are not masking tokens we

00:18:11.840 --> 00:18:19.039
mask spans of tokens which makes a more

00:18:16.240 --> 00:18:22.720
difficult problem. So a span is a

00:18:19.039 --> 00:18:24.400
subsequence of tokens and here instead

00:18:22.720 --> 00:18:26.960
of the mask token we are using the

00:18:24.400 --> 00:18:30.559
sentinel tokens which can be a

00:18:26.960 --> 00:18:34.000
subsequence each one of them and the T5

00:18:30.559 --> 00:18:36.720
model is learned to generate them. For

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:40.160
example, look at this. Uh we have this

00:18:36.720 --> 00:18:42.480
sentence that can have different way of

00:18:40.160 --> 00:18:46.400
u span corruption during the

00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:48.720
self-supervised stage. So the idea here

00:18:46.400 --> 00:18:51.200
is basically encoder learns to compress

00:18:48.720 --> 00:18:53.360
and decoder learns to generate. Now

00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:56.880
let's look at uh the decoder only

00:18:53.360 --> 00:18:59.360
architectures like GPT where they only

00:18:56.880 --> 00:19:01.679
use the decoder part or the decoder

00:18:59.360 --> 00:19:05.440
module and they use this causal self

00:19:01.679 --> 00:19:09.120
attention mask. There's a token at T

00:19:05.440 --> 00:19:10.880
only sees the previous tokens. Like I

00:19:09.120 --> 00:19:14.559
said they are designed for this auto

00:19:10.880 --> 00:19:16.640
reggressive generation tasks. The

00:19:14.559 --> 00:19:18.720
training is kind of simple because we

00:19:16.640 --> 00:19:21.039
only predict the next token given all

00:19:18.720 --> 00:19:24.000
the previous history. And this training

00:19:21.039 --> 00:19:25.679
is basically exactly the same as the

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:28.960
inference. So there's not really a

00:19:25.679 --> 00:19:32.000
mismatch. And the nice thing about this

00:19:28.960 --> 00:19:34.880
type of training is we use everything.

00:19:32.000 --> 00:19:38.480
We are not masking or corrupting a span

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:41.039
and then ask the model to predict them.

00:19:38.480 --> 00:19:43.280
Instead we ask the model to predict

00:19:41.039 --> 00:19:45.760
every token. So every token was a

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:48.400
labeled question at some point in their

00:19:45.760 --> 00:19:51.039
life. This makes this uh decoder only

00:19:48.400 --> 00:19:53.679
families very scalable in terms of data

00:19:51.039 --> 00:19:57.520
efficiency and learning. For example, we

00:19:53.679 --> 00:20:01.760
have different GPD models from 2018 to

00:19:57.520 --> 00:20:04.160
2020. And in particular, the GPT3 model

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:06.880
came up with this idea of in context

00:20:04.160 --> 00:20:10.080
learning. So you don't really need to do

00:20:06.880 --> 00:20:13.280
any fine-tuning. As long as you have a

00:20:10.080 --> 00:20:16.720
good prompt, the model can fill the

00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:19.039
answer for you. So this is by itself

00:20:16.720 --> 00:20:20.880
extremely interesting meaning that we

00:20:19.039 --> 00:20:23.440
really don't need to do any finetuning.

00:20:20.880 --> 00:20:25.919
We just train the model once and then

00:20:23.440 --> 00:20:28.880
use it. In other word no parameter

00:20:25.919 --> 00:20:31.520
updates is necessary. Instead we give a

00:20:28.880 --> 00:20:34.720
prompt for example a prompt like this

00:20:31.520 --> 00:20:38.320
that basically gives a few examples of

00:20:34.720 --> 00:20:40.640
what I want to do which here is

00:20:38.320 --> 00:20:43.120
translation from English to French and

00:20:40.640 --> 00:20:45.840
then ask the model to continue. So given

00:20:43.120 --> 00:20:48.640
this context, the model basically learns

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:51.760
a new task without changing any

00:20:48.640 --> 00:20:55.280
parameters and that's where everything

00:20:51.760 --> 00:20:58.159
is basically can be squeezed into the

00:20:55.280 --> 00:21:00.960
prompt and the model already knows to

00:20:58.159 --> 00:21:03.840
extract the patterns within that context

00:21:00.960 --> 00:21:07.280
and match those patterns and continue

00:21:03.840 --> 00:21:09.280
like that. So now really the if you

00:21:07.280 --> 00:21:11.600
provide examples in the prompt each

00:21:09.280 --> 00:21:14.000
example is like a a shot of learning

00:21:11.600 --> 00:21:16.720
like one shot is one example for example

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:20.080
here in this case we give two shots and

00:21:16.720 --> 00:21:22.880
then ask for our question so this really

00:21:20.080 --> 00:21:26.080
gives us a very efficient training for

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:29.440
auto reggressive models or GPG models

00:21:26.080 --> 00:21:32.240
because it uses the entire data and it's

00:21:29.440 --> 00:21:35.360
great for generation. We discussed this

00:21:32.240 --> 00:21:37.679
masking way of super self-supervised

00:21:35.360 --> 00:21:42.000
learning. Uh in in bird for example we

00:21:37.679 --> 00:21:44.799
only use 15% of the data as supervision

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:46.880
signal of course in a birectional way

00:21:44.799 --> 00:21:49.840
and this is great for understanding not

00:21:46.880 --> 00:21:53.360
really generating and then we discuss T5

00:21:49.840 --> 00:21:57.200
which is using both encoder and decoder

00:21:53.360 --> 00:21:59.840
very efficiently and gets benefit from

00:21:57.200 --> 00:22:02.960
the both work. Now there are ways to

00:21:59.840 --> 00:22:06.720
improve really the birth models. Uh for

00:22:02.960 --> 00:22:09.840
example there is this uh um electra

00:22:06.720 --> 00:22:13.520
solution that instead of uh doing this

00:22:09.840 --> 00:22:16.000
mask language modeling it does replacing

00:22:13.520 --> 00:22:18.640
this 15% of token with plausible

00:22:16.000 --> 00:22:20.559
alternatives and then discriminate if

00:22:18.640 --> 00:22:23.600
they are real or fake. So this way we

00:22:20.559 --> 00:22:26.080
basically provide more supervision

00:22:23.600 --> 00:22:28.880
signal from the same data. But

00:22:26.080 --> 00:22:31.200
eventually the decoder only models or at

00:22:28.880 --> 00:22:33.039
least for now they are winning and

00:22:31.200 --> 00:22:35.280
mainly because of their simple

00:22:33.039 --> 00:22:38.159
architecture they are scaling extremely

00:22:35.280 --> 00:22:41.679
well and the in context learning that

00:22:38.159 --> 00:22:44.640
emerges out of it gave rise to this chat

00:22:41.679 --> 00:22:47.200
application like chat GPT and they can

00:22:44.640 --> 00:22:49.919
do basically everything they can

00:22:47.200 --> 00:22:52.159
understand tasks they can generate tasks

00:22:49.919 --> 00:22:55.039
and they can also uh leave without

00:22:52.159 --> 00:23:01.919
fine-tuning and that's why all of this

00:22:55.039 --> 00:23:01.919
leading models GPT3, GPT4, llama, etc.
